<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-053-126 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 322 763</DOCID><JOURNAL>Los Angeles Times  Sept 26 1991 v110 pD1 23 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why Picturephones are a bad call. (video telephones) (Innovation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schrage, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Video telephones are a bad idea.andP;  The concept of integratingtelephone and video technology simply fails to respect how peoplewant to interact.andP;  Traditional telephones offer anonymity andprivacy.andP;  Callers can write letters, read newspapers or bitefingernails while conversing; they are free of the shacklingprotocols of eye contact and body language.andP;  The old Bell Systemtried to sell its Picturephone service 20 years ago and failedabysmally.andP;  Experts at the time cited high equipment andtransmission costs, but the fact is, people want to use technologyto preserve privacy and time, as well as maximize interactions andintimacies.andP;  The videophone is wrong way to integrate bandwidthcapacity into emerging telecommunications.andP;  Instead, the realfuture of the videophone is a sort of remote-controlled televisionfor offices, allowing individuals at desks to scan the nearbyconference room, or change channels to watch a meeting takingplace a continent away.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (Research).andO;Topic:     Video TelephonesCommunications TechnologyPrivacyMarket AnalysisProduct FailuresFuture Technologies.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>